1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,430
Duplicates are typically handled by finding

2
00:00:02,430 --> 00:00:04,980
the row with the right information that we want to keep.

3
00:00:04,980 --> 00:00:07,140
Let's take a look at a simple way of detecting

4
00:00:07,140 --> 00:00:10,140
duplicated rows for Pandas DataFrames in Python.

5
00:00:10,140 --> 00:00:14,235
First, we import Pandas and Numpy and load a small test scores data-set.

6
00:00:14,235 --> 00:00:17,445
We then make a copy of our original DataFrame using dot copy.

7
00:00:17,445 --> 00:00:20,250
You can see the first few rows of the DataFrame here.

8
00:00:20,250 --> 00:00:25,200
We can then access the duplicated rows for only the name and age columns by

9
00:00:25,200 --> 00:00:30,285
using the duplicated method on the clean scores DataFrame and indexing by these columns.

10
00:00:30,285 --> 00:00:34,170
The method returns a Boolean series denoting if a row is duplicated.

11
00:00:34,170 --> 00:00:36,840
Here, we see false means the row is not duplicated,

12
00:00:36,840 --> 00:00:41,025
and true means the row is duplicated here.

13
00:00:41,025 --> 00:00:44,120
An important thing to note about the duplicated method is that

14
00:00:44,120 --> 00:00:46,895
by default for each set of duplicated values,

15
00:00:46,895 --> 00:00:50,390
the first occurrence is set on false and all others on true.

16
00:00:50,390 --> 00:00:53,900
For example, when we retrieve duplicated data entries

17
00:00:53,900 --> 00:00:57,395
using this boolean series and applying the.log function,

18
00:00:57,395 --> 00:01:00,350
we're not going to see the first occurrence of the value.

19
00:01:00,350 --> 00:01:05,700
For example, Amy Linn has three test A scores as you can see here.

20
00:01:05,700 --> 00:01:10,040
But, only the first entry with the test score of 95 is not showing

21
00:01:10,040 --> 00:01:14,930
up when we try to look at the duplicated grows. Here's an additional tip.

22
00:01:14,930 --> 00:01:17,315
If there are duplicate rows and you want to drop them,

23
00:01:17,315 --> 00:01:19,325
keep a record of two things.

24
00:01:19,325 --> 00:01:23,210
One, the number of duplicate rows in the original dataset.

25
00:01:23,210 --> 00:01:27,805
We can get the number of duplicated rows by running df.duplicated.sum.

26
00:01:27,805 --> 00:01:30,125
Second, you want to keep in mind

27
00:01:30,125 --> 00:01:33,085
additional data around where the duplicates are occurring.

28
00:01:33,085 --> 00:01:35,270
For example, with this data we can make

29
00:01:35,270 --> 00:01:39,155
some informative assumptions around how prone the data is having two duplicates.

30
00:01:39,155 --> 00:01:42,560
For example, using visual inspection of this entire small DataFrame,

31
00:01:42,560 --> 00:01:43,835
we can ask the question,

32
00:01:43,835 --> 00:01:46,820
are all students that are 15 somehow having

33
00:01:46,820 --> 00:01:49,940
duplicate entries compared to students who are 14?

34
00:01:49,940 --> 00:01:51,410
Perhaps this may be because

35
00:01:51,410 --> 00:01:54,050
all the 15-year-olds are in a different class than the 14-year-olds,

36
00:01:54,050 --> 00:01:57,500
and there were data entry issues for the 15-year-old's classroom.

37
00:01:57,500 --> 00:01:59,455
However, there is a question.

38
00:01:59,455 --> 00:02:00,815
In the first scenario,

39
00:02:00,815 --> 00:02:03,710
if the duplicated rows are entirely the same,

40
00:02:03,710 --> 00:02:07,780
including the test score like the first and last row that we can see here,

41
00:02:07,780 --> 00:02:10,550
we know that the same data was probably entered

42
00:02:10,550 --> 00:02:14,290
twice and we can safely keep one row and remove the others.

43
00:02:14,290 --> 00:02:16,100
But in this case,

44
00:02:16,100 --> 00:02:18,860
Amy has different scores on test A.

45
00:02:18,860 --> 00:02:22,340
How do you determine which row to delete?

46
00:02:22,340 --> 00:02:26,060
In these scenarios with duplicated rows containing different values,

47
00:02:26,060 --> 00:02:28,810
we need additional information to help make the decision.

48
00:02:28,810 --> 00:02:32,465
For example, we may need to check with the data providers like their teachers

49
00:02:32,465 --> 00:02:36,335
to understand what rows are incorrect and if they need to be removed,

50
00:02:36,335 --> 00:02:40,265
then you can remove the data if it is incorrect or keep the data if it is correct.

51
00:02:40,265 --> 00:02:43,010
For example, in this case, seeing how Amy has a score

52
00:02:43,010 --> 00:02:46,480
of 95 and 85 on test A at the same time.

53
00:02:46,480 --> 00:02:49,730
Sometimes, the scenario can get even more complicated.

54
00:02:49,730 --> 00:02:53,690
For example, take a look at this new column that popped up test B score,

55
00:02:53,690 --> 00:02:58,070
which contains students scores now on a different test in addition to test A.

56
00:02:58,070 --> 00:03:03,895
They're duplicated rows with different values in both test A and test B square columns.

57
00:03:03,895 --> 00:03:06,110
To make the decision on how to deal with this,

58
00:03:06,110 --> 00:03:08,600
we also need to check the data providers again.

59
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:11,270
Let's say after checking with data providers,

60
00:03:11,270 --> 00:03:14,030
we confirm that the duplicated data in some of

61
00:03:14,030 --> 00:03:18,425
the test A scores column values are incorrect and we should remove them,

62
00:03:18,425 --> 00:03:22,355
but the test B score column has correct values.

63
00:03:22,355 --> 00:03:27,050
The data has duplicated rows because the students did take test b multiple times,

64
00:03:27,050 --> 00:03:30,010
and all scores should be kept in the table.

65
00:03:30,010 --> 00:03:35,420
In order to do this, you may consider marking the incorrect duplicate values that

66
00:03:35,420 --> 00:03:40,435
we know for the test A score are there as NaNs and treating them as such.

67
00:03:40,435 --> 00:03:43,880
You may also consider simplifying your data structure, for example,

68
00:03:43,880 --> 00:03:47,600
creating a separate table for the repeated values in test B score if

69
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:49,430
the structure is significantly different from

70
00:03:49,430 --> 00:03:52,210
the test A square and the rest of the columns.

71
00:03:52,210 --> 00:03:56,440
Let's talk about how to implement the code to remove the duplicated rows.

72
00:03:56,440 --> 00:03:59,405
For the data frame with only the test A score column,

73
00:03:59,405 --> 00:04:01,190
in order to drop the duplicated rows,

74
00:04:01,190 --> 00:04:02,225
you can use pandas,

75
00:04:02,225 --> 00:04:03,650
drop duplicates function,

76
00:04:03,650 --> 00:04:08,255
specifying the subset parameter as the columns we want to use to identify the duplicates.

77
00:04:08,255 --> 00:04:10,940
By default, this parameter is set to all columns,

78
00:04:10,940 --> 00:04:14,040
but here we'd like to narrow it down to name and age.

79
00:04:14,040 --> 00:04:18,260
By default, this function will drop all duplicates except for the first occurrence.

80
00:04:18,260 --> 00:04:23,675
For example, the first entry where anyone's test score is 95 where the index is zero,

81
00:04:23,675 --> 00:04:28,085
will be kept but all later entries of hers will be deleted as we see here.

82
00:04:28,085 --> 00:04:33,610
We can also set the key parameter to last four drop duplicates to,

83
00:04:33,610 --> 00:04:38,320
for example, drop duplicates except for the last occurrence of a value in our dataset.

84
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:42,790
As you can see here, Amy Linn's first entry with index 0 is deleted,

85
00:04:42,790 --> 00:04:45,965
but the last entry with index 11 is kept.

86
00:04:45,965 --> 00:04:48,910
As we can see here now using the.sum method,

87
00:04:48,910 --> 00:04:53,345
the number of duplicated rows after applying drop duplicates is zero.

88
00:04:53,345 --> 00:04:58,630
What if the value you want to keep is neither the first occurrence nor the last?

89
00:04:58,630 --> 00:05:01,065
Drop duplicates is not going to help you here.

90
00:05:01,065 --> 00:05:03,040
For example, consider that we want to keep

91
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:05,710
the first and last occurrences of Amy's data,

92
00:05:05,710 --> 00:05:09,555
but we don't want to keep the middle row with the index 5.

93
00:05:09,555 --> 00:05:13,870
In this case, you can actually remove this row using the drop method,

94
00:05:13,870 --> 00:05:16,535
and specifying the index of the row,

95
00:05:16,535 --> 00:05:18,310
which in this case is five.

96
00:05:18,310 --> 00:05:21,320
Note how the middle duplicated is gone from

97
00:05:21,320 --> 00:05:25,195
the DataFrame we specifically retrieved Amy Linn's scores.

98
00:05:25,195 --> 00:05:30,345
For this DataFrame that had both the test A and test B scores,

99
00:05:30,345 --> 00:05:36,200
let's say we want to replace the incorrect test A value on duplicated rows as NaN values.

100
00:05:36,200 --> 00:05:41,050
We can first access the index of the duplicated rows using.index to do this.

101
00:05:41,050 --> 00:05:44,800
Here, we see the duplicated rows are indexes 5, 9 and 10.

102
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:49,890
Then we can locate these incorrect test A values by using the.loc

103
00:05:49,890 --> 00:05:52,710
method and specifying this dupe index variable

104
00:05:52,710 --> 00:05:55,430
as our rows and the test A scores our column.

105
00:05:55,430 --> 00:05:57,680
We then want to set these values that are in

106
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:00,095
the test A score column that we know are incorrect,

107
00:06:00,095 --> 00:06:05,440
and are belonging to the duplicated rows to a numpy.nan value.

108
00:06:05,440 --> 00:06:08,370
Let's now look at this DataFrame result again

109
00:06:08,370 --> 00:06:11,265
with the test A score and the test B values.

110
00:06:11,265 --> 00:06:18,245
Note how there aren't any ends now in the test A score column for rows 5, 9 and 10.

111
00:06:18,245 --> 00:06:20,105
But the first occurrences of the data,

112
00:06:20,105 --> 00:06:22,685
like Amy Linn's record, is kept intact.

113
00:06:22,685 --> 00:06:24,950
Now we can meaningfully balance between

114
00:06:24,950 --> 00:06:27,710
the NaN and incorrect values in the test A score,

115
00:06:27,710 --> 00:06:30,080
and the meaningful values that we want to keep as

116
00:06:30,080 --> 00:06:33,510
part of the test B score as part of this DataFrame.

